</div>
</div>
<p>African rice has been cultivated for 3500 years. Between 1500 and 800 BC, <i><a href="/wiki/Oryza_glaberrima" title="Oryza glaberrima">Oryza glaberrima</a></i> propagated from its original centre, the <a href="/wiki/Niger_River" title="Niger River">Niger River</a> <a href="/wiki/River_delta" title="River delta">delta</a>, and extended to Senegal. However, it never developed far from its original region. Its cultivation even declined in favour of the Asian species, which was introduced to East Africa early in the common era and spread westward.<sup id="cite_ref-46" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-46">[46]</a></sup> African rice helped Africa conquer its famine of 1203.<sup id="cite_ref-National_Academies_Press_47-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-National_Academies_Press-47">[47]</a></sup></p>
